From c18773a196e1eb96251aea870065dcfc1d709bd4 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Micheal Waltz <micheal@ecliptik.com>
Date: Sat, 25 Apr 2026 11:24:12 -0700
Subject: [PATCH] [DOSKUTSU] sdl3: convert remaining SDL2-style include paths
 to SDL3-style
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Follow-up to patch 0010 (sdl3-mechanical-renames). 0010 covered the
bulk SDL2→SDL3 API renames (SDL_RenderCopy → SDL_RenderTexture,
SDL_FreeSurface → SDL_DestroySurface, etc.) but missed converting the
SDL2-era include paths to SDL3-era include paths. Result: Phase 5
attempt 3 hit `fatal error: SDL.h: No such file or directory` on
`src/floattext.h:4` and likely several other sites that use #include
<SDL.h> instead of the SDL3-prefixed #include <SDL3/SDL.h>.

Numbered 0010a (alpha-suffix between 0010 and 0011) to keep 0010
immutable — preserves nxengine's #30 review on the original 26 KB
mechanical-renames patch. apply-patches.sh's lexical ordering picks
up 0010a in sequence.

================================================================
What changed
================================================================

20 #include site conversions across 18 files in src/:

  #include <SDL.h>            →  #include <SDL3/SDL.h>            (16 sites)
  #include "SDL.h"            →  #include <SDL3/SDL.h>            (1 site, src/graphics/zoom.h —
                                                                   normalized to angle-bracket form to
                                                                   match every other include site)
  #include <SDL_image.h>      →  #include <SDL3_image/SDL_image.h>  (2 sites)
  #include <SDL_mixer.h>      →  #include <SDL3_mixer/SDL_mixer.h>  (1 site)

Files touched (full list):
  src/common/misc.cpp
  src/console.cpp
  src/debug.cpp
  src/floattext.h           ← Phase 5 attempt 3's specific failure site
  src/graphics/Font.cpp
  src/graphics/Font.h
  src/graphics/Renderer.cpp
  src/graphics/Renderer.h
  src/graphics/Surface.h
  src/graphics/pngfuncs.h
  src/graphics/types.h
  src/graphics/zoom.h
  src/input.h
  src/main.cpp
  src/niku.cpp
  src/nx.h
  src/profile.cpp
  src/settings.cpp

================================================================
Why this slipped past 0010
================================================================

0010 (sdl3-mechanical-renames.patch, 26 KB) used regex-based
identifier renames targeting SDL2 function/type/enum names
(SDL_RenderCopy etc.). The include-path conversions are syntactically
distinct — `#include <SDL.h>` doesn't contain any of the renamed
identifiers, so the original sweep didn't catch them. Different
search pattern, different sweep needed. Easy miss in retrospect.

The audio cluster (0013-0017) caught its own audio-side includes
(`#include <SDL_mixer.h>` in Pixtone.cpp, Organya.cpp, Ogg.cpp,
SoundManager.h/cpp) because that work was scoped to src/sound/ and
naturally rewrote those sites. The graphics + core .h/.cpp files
outside src/sound/ were the gap.

================================================================
Why no behavioral change
================================================================

These are header-file location changes only. The SDL3 API surfaces
the same types/functions through the SDL3-prefixed paths; no source
code logic changes. Pure path rename.

The vendor/SDL/include/SDL3/SDL.h header still re-exports the full
SDL3 API (including the SDL_image and SDL_mixer companion libraries
when their headers are also pulled in via the SDL3_image/, SDL3_mixer/
prefixed paths). So all transitively-included symbols continue to
resolve identically.

================================================================
Validation
================================================================

Build verification deferred to build-engineer's next `make nxengine`
attempt (Phase 5 attempt 4). Expected: the floattext.h compile error
goes away; if any further include paths are missing they'll surface
as new "No such file or directory" errors at compile time and trigger
a 0010b follow-up. Doesn't affect runtime behaviour either way —
this is pure compile-time path resolution.
